<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911105-0147</DOCNO><DOCID>911105-0147.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor --   New British Library:   Quality, Speedy Service</HL><DATE>11/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19</SO><RE>EUROPE (EU)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   In response to Paul Levy's article, &quot;Readers Revolt OverNew British Library&quot; (Leisure andamp; Arts, Oct. 2), I should liketo reassure your readers that the new building underconstruction, far from &quot;losing its charm&quot; for government,represents a positive and tangible demonstration of theBritish government's belief in its national library's centralrole in information storage, preservation and retrieval.   The new building will allow the library the opportunitynot only to care properly for its unrivaled collections,books, manuscripts and documents, but also to improve thequality and speed of service to its readers, from both thearts and sciences. In addition, the library will be able tomake its collections accessible to a wider public through anexpanded program of exhibitions and events.</LP><TEXT>   The new British Library will be a first-rate buildingoffering first-rate services.   Brian Lang   Chief Executive   The British Library   London</TEXT></DOC>